    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-05-04T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-05-04T07:00:00-05:00" n="449"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d449">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 EW/5–445: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]<note n="77" xml:id="d449fn1">For remainder
                            of this telegram, see <ref target="frus1945v03#pg_775">vol. <hi
                                    rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p. 775</ref>.</note>
                    </seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-05-04T14:00:00+02:00"
                            >May 4, 1945—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 10:07 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2345. For Matthews<note n="78" xml:id="d449fn2">H. Freeman Matthews, Director of
                        the Office of European Affairs.</note> from Murphy.<note n="78a"
                        xml:id="d449fn3">Robert D. Murphy, U.S. Political Adviser for
                        Germany.</note>
                </p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <p>Regarding Czechoslovakia the British of course are pressing for continued advance
                    into that country and it looks as if we may advance up to the line of the
                        Moldau<note n="79" xml:id="d449fn4">In Czech, the Vltava River.</note> for
                    operational reasons. British reasoning explains their proposals for a civil
                    affairs agreement with the Czechs which they have been promoting. It should be
                    noted that the proposed agreement is between the Supreme Commander and the Czech
                    Government and not between the Czechs and the United States and British
                    Governments. [Murphy.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
